My Review: I borrowed the audiobook version from the library, and I think the book would have been a better choice. I made it about two-thirds of the way through and couldn’t do it anymore. It should have stopped one story after the revelations about struggling through depression and just being yourself- then I would have really enjoyed it. There was the authenticity of the author telling her own story and the way her inflections and noises round out the emotions and land the jokes, but after a while the book just turned into her rambling about strange things that have happened to her. Way to be yourself, but I could have used a little less of it.

My Review:
I was so torn about what rating to give this book. At some points, a 5, but at others, a 3, so I settled on a 4.
At times it was too distracted from the point. The author is a travel writer and it shows, but it doesn’t add much. He described whatever little tale from the field struck his fancy, meandering through it before abruptly returning to the point. Sometimes entertaining, but mostly distracting and confusing.
Very well-written and well-researched, albeit unfocused. Certainly thought-provoking, but it would have been more enjoyable if it were shorter.
Also no concluding chapter? After all that time invested I would have liked a neat little summary as something to digest, a parting thought.

Title: Brain on Fire: My Month of Madness
Author: Susannah Cahalan
My Review: Susannah Cahalan is a great storyteller, beginning with an excellent hook and coming back to it in the end with new revelations, bringing the story full circle. It’s a true story, but she tells it with the detail and emotion that makes you hungry for more, rare in a nonfiction book. I loved every moment from her bizarre reporting experiences to her detailed descriptions of how it felt to not understand yourself. She is somehow able to objectively describe these deeply personal themes, piecing together the story from the memories of everyone involved, each incomplete because of PTSD from the experience. She opens up fully to the reader, exposing her deepest thoughts and emotions, and winning me over with her vulnerability. “I wouldn’t take that terrible experience back for anything in the world. Too much light has come out of my darkness.”

Title: Being Wrong: Adventures in the Margin of Error
Author: Kathryn Schulz
My Review:
“Even if you can’t be brought to believe that error itself is a good thing, I hope to convince you by the end of this book that it is inseparably linked to other good things, things we definitely do not want to illuminate – like, say, our intelligence.” Making a mistake might not feel good, but error is akin in spirit to hope. When viewed with a positive attitude, error represents a false view of reality, and therefore opportunity for growth and improvement. “To fuck up is to find adventure: it is in that spirit that this book is written.”
Why is it that we have so much trouble accepting our own fallibility? This book explores that theme and more in finer detail than you’d ever think would be interesting. There are so many aspects of our lives in which we are wrong, and yet we can’t seem to understand that to err is human, let alone accept it. This aptly-named book teaches us not how to avoid making mistakes but how to keep an open mind and embrace our imperfections.

Title: The Girl with the Lower Back Tattoo
Author: Amy Schumer
My Review:
Maybe a little too honest. And definitely grasping for content.
This book was such a letdown because I think Amy is really funny sometimes, but now she just looks selfish and shallow to me.
Noveau riche: just her bragging about how nice it is to have a lot of money. Acknowledging that the reader probably hates it does not make it okay. She thinks she’s cool and generous because she buys her friends sushi.
And a whole chapter dedicated to your stuffed animals? No.
She tried to be an inspiring role model, but there were too many attempted messages for that to be effective.

Title: Warped Passages: Unraveling the Mysteries of the Universe's Hidden Dimensions
Author: Lisa Randall
My Review:
I have to admit that much of the content went over my head, even as a scientist. The scale of quantum particles is just too difficult to comprehend. Probably not the subject matter that is going to succeed with the general public.

I admire Lisa Randall for what she is doing here. She is explaining complex mathematical concepts to the layperson using analogies in the most accessible way possible. I understand these cutting edge physics concepts now better than before, but unfortunately I still feel in the dark. Love that she tried though, and maybe if I read enough of these types of books, I’ll finally get it.
She used a West Side Story reference to explain a physics concept. What a nerd.

Title: The Geometry of Wealth: How to shape a life of money and meaning

Title: Run Away

My Review: For much of the book, I felt like I kept waiting for the plot to happen, and it never did. It wasn’t until very near the end that the clouds lifted and the dots connected. I wanted the reveal to happen earlier with an exciting fallout for the rest of the story. By the time it got to the point it was kind of anticlimactic, but it was an interesting read that kept me hooked to learn the explanation.

Title: A Very Large Expanse of Sea
Author: Tahereh Mafi
My Review: I loved the novelty of a Muslim main character, but that was about the only thing I liked in this book. The plot was just a girl navigating high school and falling for a guy, and getting together once they realize they both feel stereotyped, and it all falling apart because of racism. There is very little character development. The climax is a single breakdancing performance, before which everyone is so rude to her, and afterward they really like her. Yeah right. Not particularly amazing writing, but I do wish I could have read this book when I was in high school to think about the experiences of minorities.

The action starts immediately, which means the reader is desperately trying to keep up while being totally in the dark about how and why these things are happening. There were, however, some interesting historical elements to the story that I wish had been incorporated better.

Title: The Cruel Prince (The Folk of the Air, #1)

Publisher: Little, Brown Books for Young Readers
My Review: This was my first fantasy book in a long time. It was hard for me to get back into reading about faeries and magic at first, but once I got over my personal mental block, I enjoyed the story. It was interesting to me to see how the fantasy genre has evolved since I was a kid. I think contemporary young adult books are good to read occasionally because they are a reflection of the current cultural norms and values. There are many underpinned themes of cultural and personal differences and acceptance of those who are not like yourself... too many themes. I wanted the author to pick one and stick to it. It was difficult to get in to, however by halfway through enough interesting plot points were happening and it tended towards being more action-packed that I continued. It had the plot but not quite the character development and complexity that I wanted in a story like this. Really, it just made me want to read Harry Potter again... (so I did).

Title: Educated
Author: Tara Westover
My Review:
A story of personal growth, focusing on a tension between family commitment and a newfound internal drive. Tara Westover describes her experiences of bonding and estrangement with her family, relying on anecdotes to build the mountain west world that I’ve never seen but now feel like I understand better. She has a unique perspective of paying homage to this world in which she grew up, but has now decided to leave behind after having been exposed to the outside world and education. I wish she had talked more about her educational experiences, how hard it must have been for her with no previous formal schooling, but that was not the main point of the story.
In the enlightened conclusion, Tara describes two versions of herself: one as she was at 16, obedient to her family, and the other as she is now, independent and strong. She describes the moment she knew that the former was gone, shed like an old skin. “You could call this selfhood many things. Metamorphosis. Falsity. Betrayal. I call it an education.”

Title: Sourdough
Author: Robin Sloan
My Review: Tech chick discovers joy in home-baked bread and enters another world in the multiverse of San Francisco. This was a hyperbolic story- the main character is a little too focused on her job, a little too inept with food, and a little too in love with her bread. The inauthentic beginning turned promising middle turned hastily-constructed ending (reminiscent of King Kong) was overly ludicrous. I’m sure a more believable true version of this story already exists somewhere in San Francisco, and I wish Robin Sloan had found that person and introduced them to the world, rather than the fictional Lois.

Title: Kitchen Confidential: Adventures in the Culinary Underbelly
Author: Anthony Bourdain
My Review: With the passing of Anthony Bourdain, I moved this book to the top of my list, and am so glad I did. Well-written, and endlessly informative and entertaining. This set of stories and advice from his life paints the picture of an impressive man who accomplished so much because of his propensity to try new things and learn from his mistakes.

Title: The Picture of Dorian Gray

My Review: This is a philosophical book about narcissism and happiness that was at times thought-provoking, but saying I truly enjoyed it would be a lie. It had its place in history, but is one of those classics you read in school and never again.

Title: Code Girls: The Untold Story of the American Women Code Breakers Who Helped Win World War II
Author: Liza Mundy
My Review: I love the topic of this book. These women are so obviously strong and inspiring and I love learning more about them in this well-researched book. They were extremely brave and hardworking in the face of real danger for their friends and families, overcoming the emotional toll of war to persist in their work. That said, I think the information was a little disjointed, being more a list of facts than a story. Parts of it were better about this than others. It just seemed like the author had read a bunch of their journals and letters and stuck the interesting pieces together, not entirely cohesively. Still, overall, I enjoyed reading about the details of these women’s lives at an important time in history, and the underappreciated work they did for our country.

Title: I, Robot (Robot, #0.1)
Author: Isaac Asimov
Bookshelves: fiction, science-fiction, kindle, classics, philosophy, space, made-into-movie, favorites
Bookshelves with positions: fiction (#124), science-fiction (#7), kindle (#264), classics (#118), philosophy (#21), space (#43), made-into-movie (#104), favorites (#42)
My Review: This was my first adventure into Asimov’s work. I thought this book was going to be a dense, boring look into the future of humanity in harmony with robotics, but I was happily proved wrong. It’s a unified collection of short stories in which humans are proud of their constructed robots, erroneously assuming that they have built them perfectly to do a certain job, but mistakes in logic prevent the robot from completing its purpose in the intended way. To take a quote from the book, “it is built by humans and is therefore built according to human values.” The whole book makes the reader contemplate what it means to be human.
